[Bovine tuberculosis is a chronic bacterial disease caused by the
acid-fast, slow-growing rod-shaped _Mycobacterium bovis_; transmission to
humans constitutes a public health problem.
[Bovine] tuberculosis (TB) can produce internal lesions in animals.
[Bovine] TB can be spread within a herd when an infected animal coughs,
releasing bacteria-laden mucus onto feed that is consumed, or into the air
that is inhaled by nearby cows.
Aerosol exposure to _M. bovis_ is considered to be the most frequent route
of infection of cattle, but infection by ingestion of contaminated material
also occurs. Characteristic tuberculous lesions occur most frequently in
the lungs and the retropharyngeal, bronchial, and mediastinal lymph nodes.
Lesions can also be found in the mesenteric lymph nodes, liver, spleen, on
serous membranes, and in other organs. - Mod.TG]
